{
  "$schema": "../../schema/pathway.schema.json",
  "id": "citric-acid-cycle",
  "name": "Citric acid cycle (TCA / Krebs cycle)",
  "category": "energy-metabolism",
  "summary": "The eight-step mitochondrial cycle that fully oxidizes acetyl-CoA to two CO2, conserving the energy as 3 NADH, 1 FADH2 (delivered as ubiquinol) and 1 GTP per turn.",
  "description": "The citric acid cycle (tricarboxylic acid / TCA cycle, or Krebs cycle) is the central hub of aerobic energy metabolism. Each turn condenses one acetyl-CoA (2 carbons) with oxaloacetate (4 carbons) to citrate (6 carbons), then releases two carbons as CO2 and regenerates oxaloacetate. The energy of oxidation is captured as three NADH, one FADH2 (passed directly to the ubiquinone pool by Complex II) and one GTP (or ATP) via substrate-level phosphorylation. Beyond catabolism the cycle is profoundly amphibolic: intermediates are withdrawn (cataplerosis) for gluconeogenesis (oxaloacetate), amino-acid and nitrogen metabolism (2-oxoglutarate, oxaloacetate), heme synthesis (succinyl-CoA) and cytosolic lipogenesis (citrate), and are replenished by anaplerotic routes such as pyruvate carboxylase and glutaminolysis. Flux is governed at three effectively irreversible steps — citrate synthase, NAD+-isocitrate dehydrogenase and the alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase complex — by substrate supply, the NADH/NAD+ and ATP/ADP ratios, and matrix Ca2+. The pyruvate dehydrogenase complex, which supplies acetyl-CoA from glycolytic pyruvate, is included here as the committed bridge reaction and is switched on/off by a dedicated kinase/phosphatase (PDK/PDP) system.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["ubiquitous", "heart", "skeletal-muscle", "liver", "kidney", "brain", "brown-adipose"],
  "keywords": ["TCA cycle", "Krebs cycle", "citric acid cycle", "acetyl-CoA", "oxaloacetate", "mitochondrion", "central carbon metabolism", "anaplerosis", "cataplerosis", "substrate-level phosphorylation"],
